-- Japan, China, Malaysia, Taiwan, Singapore: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- David Yong
-- 2010-07-21T22:09:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/japan-china-malaysia-taiwan-singapore-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry will release at
1:30 p.m. in Tokyo its data on the all-industry activity index
in May. The index probably fell 0.4 percent from April, when it
rose 1.8 percent, according to a Bloomberg News survey of
economists.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.085 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The yen traded at
86.95 per dollar at 6:57 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: China Development Bank will today sell 20 billion
yuan ($2.95 billion) of 10-year bonds and 10 billion yuan of
seven-year floating-rate notes. The People’s Bank of China plans
to sell 80 billion yuan of three-month bills.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.54 percent. The yuan was at 6.777 per dollar.  
 Malaysia: The government will today sell 100 million
ringgit ($31 million) of six-month bills. They yielded 2.758
percent at the previous sale on July 8. It may also disclose the
amount of 2017 bonds it will auction next week.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.37 percent. The ringgit was at 3.2160 per dollar.  
 Singapore: Inflation accelerated 3.5 percent in June from a
year earlier, according to a Bloomberg survey before a
government report due tomorrow. Prices rose 3.2 percent in May.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due in September 2020
was 2.26 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3790 per
dollar.  
 Taiwan: The seasonally adjusted unemployment rate probably
dropped to 5.16 percent in June from 5.22 percent in May,
according to a Bloomberg survey before a statistics bureau
report due at 4 p.m. today. Industrial production rose 22
percent in June from a year earlier, following a 30.67 percent
gain in May, according to a separate survey before a government
report tomorrow.  
 The government will sell NT$35 billion ($1.09 billion) of
91-day treasury bills tomorrow.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent note due March 2020 was
1.399 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$32.15 per dollar.  
 Thailand: The central bank will publish tomorrow its new
forecasts for economic growth and inflation for 2010 and 2011.
Growth may be as strong as 5.8 percent this year and 5 percent
in 2011, according to its April estimates.  
 The government will, on the same day, sell a total of 10
billion baht ($310 million) of bills maturing in 28, 91 and 182
days.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent note maturing in May 2015
was 2.971 percent. The baht was at 32.30 per dollar.  
